WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.990 --> 00:00:05.585
Prof: Did I tell you the
story when one of my friends was

00:00:05.585 --> 00:00:07.070
offered--to buy from me?
 

00:00:07.070 --> 00:00:11.705
I was in upper Egypt and I was
traveling with a young lady,

00:00:11.705 --> 00:00:14.662
and a third woman,
a little bit older,

00:00:14.662 --> 00:00:18.310
sort of was traveling alone;
it's not terribly comfortable.

00:00:18.310 --> 00:00:22.963
She asked to join us I and said
'that's fine,' so the three of

00:00:22.963 --> 00:00:25.710
us were sitting there near
Aswan,

00:00:25.710 --> 00:00:31.470
and there were two men sitting
sort of across the room.

00:00:31.470 --> 00:00:33.450
One of them dressed in clearly
Arab garb,

00:00:33.450 --> 00:00:36.830
and one dressed in a rather
modern suit,

00:00:36.830 --> 00:00:40.840
and at some point the guy in
the suit came over,

00:00:40.840 --> 00:00:44.141
introduced himself very
politely, and he was a

00:00:44.141 --> 00:00:48.470
Palestinian and the other man
was a Saudi Arabian sheik,

00:00:48.470 --> 00:00:55.241
and they had noticed that I had
two wives and so the sheik had

00:00:55.241 --> 00:00:58.196
wanted to know--
would like to purchase the

00:00:58.196 --> 00:01:00.759
second--the older one,
the second wife from me.

00:01:00.759 --> 00:01:04.798
Since it was the somewhat older
one, he thought I wouldn't mind

00:01:04.798 --> 00:01:05.578
very much.
 

00:01:05.578 --> 00:01:08.269
It was a wonderful scene
because, as you know,

00:01:08.269 --> 00:01:10.540
Palestinians are very
sophisticated;

00:01:10.540 --> 00:01:14.161
they've been living with Jews,
who are basically Europeans,

00:01:14.161 --> 00:01:17.720
for a very long time so they're
just like anybody else.

00:01:17.720 --> 00:01:22.530
The Saudi Arabian sheik was
obviously living,

00:01:22.530 --> 00:01:25.813
not in the modern world and
this poor Palestinian had to

00:01:25.813 --> 00:01:28.351
intermediate,
so he was very scared how I

00:01:28.351 --> 00:01:29.230
would respond.
 

00:01:29.230 --> 00:01:31.286
Would I make a scene,
would I slug him,

00:01:31.286 --> 00:01:34.208
would I try to get him
arrested, or any of this sort of

00:01:34.208 --> 00:01:34.750
stuff?
 

00:01:34.750 --> 00:01:38.285
Of course it was immediately
obvious to me what was going on

00:01:38.285 --> 00:01:41.819
and to my two lady friends and
so we played it very cool and

00:01:41.819 --> 00:01:43.848
we,
you know--please sit down,

00:01:43.848 --> 00:01:47.057
let's discuss this,
how old is the sheik,

00:01:47.057 --> 00:01:50.599
how many wives does he already
have,

00:01:50.599 --> 00:01:53.714
how many has he divorced,
does he have any concubines in

00:01:53.714 --> 00:01:56.494
addition to his wives,
how much money do you have,

00:01:56.494 --> 00:01:57.050
etc., etc.
 

00:01:57.050 --> 00:02:00.132
We had a very,
very nice polite thing and you

00:02:00.132 --> 00:02:04.546
could just see the intermediary
his face just relaxed because he

00:02:04.546 --> 00:02:07.140
was expecting something
terrible.

00:02:07.140 --> 00:02:09.979
Everybody played along and it
went off very well,

00:02:09.979 --> 00:02:15.798
and in the middle of this the
sheik calls the intermediary

00:02:15.798 --> 00:02:19.921
over back to him,
and they talk something and out

00:02:19.921 --> 00:02:23.952
comes a velvet purse given to
the Palestinian and he gives it

00:02:23.952 --> 00:02:28.050
to me as a sign of good faith on
the part of the Arabian,

00:02:28.050 --> 00:02:29.520
he wanted me to have this.
 

00:02:29.520 --> 00:02:30.288
What is it?
 

00:02:30.288 --> 00:02:34.099
A set of Muslim prayer beads,
beautiful cat's-eye stones,

00:02:34.099 --> 00:02:37.910
many--not just a chain but
beautiful, beautiful handiwork

00:02:37.910 --> 00:02:40.020
and probably very valuable.
 

00:02:40.020 --> 00:02:42.998
I was looking for--to bring to
class--actually last time and I

00:02:42.998 --> 00:02:44.270
can't find it right now.
 

00:02:44.270 --> 00:02:47.634
Everything worked out,
the women paid very great

00:02:47.634 --> 00:02:51.675
attention to what was going on,
and we said politely at the end

00:02:51.675 --> 00:02:54.628
that we would consider and give
them an answer tomorrow.

00:02:54.628 --> 00:02:59.520
In the end she didn't want to
be bought, even though she's

00:02:59.520 --> 00:03:04.581
obviously going to have some
good chunk of change out of it,

00:03:04.581 --> 00:03:06.468
or at least I was.
 

00:03:06.468 --> 00:03:14.139
Two things will have to be
delayed because Eliezeri is not

00:03:14.139 --> 00:03:19.792
here and we have to add
something to Noah's

00:03:19.792 --> 00:03:22.080
presentation.
 

00:03:22.080 --> 00:03:27.628
Let's skip that.
 

00:03:27.628 --> 00:03:32.377
Last time we were discussing
Europe and we were coming into

00:03:32.377 --> 00:03:34.256
the--
we started to discuss the

00:03:34.256 --> 00:03:37.390
Middle Ages and we start with
Europe because we have the best

00:03:37.390 --> 00:03:37.810
data.
 

00:03:37.810 --> 00:03:39.566
We have very,
very good data about lots and

00:03:39.566 --> 00:03:40.780
lots of things from Europe.
 

00:03:40.780 --> 00:03:45.639
It's not so good from the rest
of the world.

00:03:45.639 --> 00:03:49.883
From about--for about 500
years, from 1200 to 1700 the

00:03:49.883 --> 00:03:54.206
data, poor as the data is,
shows that population really

00:03:54.206 --> 00:03:56.610
didn't rise terribly much.
 

00:03:56.610 --> 00:03:59.639
They were in some sort of
stasis.

00:03:59.639 --> 00:04:05.310
The reasons for this we had
discussed a little bit.

00:04:05.310 --> 00:04:10.421
We talked about the plague,
and the plague lasted like 500

00:04:10.421 --> 00:04:17.559
years--
this is--remember the plague

00:04:17.559 --> 00:04:32.024
hit Europe in 1347 so this table
where they have good data starts

00:04:32.024 --> 00:04:36.319
200 years later.
 

00:04:36.319 --> 00:04:40.341
The plague has been around for
200 years and still there's a

00:04:40.341 --> 00:04:42.913
number of cases;
that's not individuals but

00:04:42.913 --> 00:04:46.067
different cities and places in
which there was an outbreak and

00:04:46.067 --> 00:04:49.170
we just don't have good records
of how many people died,

00:04:49.170 --> 00:04:53.021
but 1550,1600,
1650, see the plague is dying

00:04:53.021 --> 00:04:57.639
out slowly and there's many,
many theories whether people

00:04:57.639 --> 00:05:00.956
got resistance to it,
or the rats that carried it,

00:05:00.956 --> 00:05:04.439
died or were out-competed by
another species of rats.

00:05:04.439 --> 00:05:08.259
Not known, but the plague did
eventually die out.

00:05:08.259 --> 00:05:14.759
From 1347 to 1849,
is 500 years where the plague

00:05:14.759 --> 00:05:17.250
keeps recurring.
 

00:05:17.250 --> 00:05:21.353
That was clearly one of the
reasons why population couldn't

00:05:21.353 --> 00:05:21.850
grow.
 

00:05:21.850 --> 00:05:25.310
Then there was violence,
there was constant small level

00:05:25.310 --> 00:05:27.764
violence,
and then when the Protestant

00:05:27.764 --> 00:05:32.216
Reformation happened,
the religious wars broke out

00:05:32.216 --> 00:05:38.459
and according to one of the
standard textbooks of European

00:05:38.459 --> 00:05:43.060
history they ran from 1531 up to
1657,

00:05:43.060 --> 00:05:46.877
so another 130 years of
slaughter and they rolled around

00:05:46.877 --> 00:05:48.889
different places in Europe.
 

00:05:48.889 --> 00:05:52.839
By the time they were done the
most contested--

00:05:52.839 --> 00:05:56.093
southern Europe stayed
Catholic, and very northern

00:05:56.093 --> 00:06:00.144
Europe became Protestant but the
middle of Europe was strongly

00:06:00.144 --> 00:06:02.995
contested--
and so something like a third

00:06:02.995 --> 00:06:06.581
to a half of everybody got
killed in this time because of

00:06:06.581 --> 00:06:07.990
the religious wars.
 

00:06:07.990 --> 00:06:12.367
This is the period that Malthus
is describing and we'll come

00:06:12.367 --> 00:06:15.560
back to Malthus--that Malthus
knew about.

00:06:15.560 --> 00:06:18.980
This is the history that he
understood and we'll come back

00:06:18.980 --> 00:06:22.862
to what his theories were,
but the historians now agree

00:06:22.862 --> 00:06:26.230
pretty much that productivity of
the land,

00:06:26.230 --> 00:06:29.086
especially agriculture,
because that was the main

00:06:29.086 --> 00:06:31.942
occupation,
was rising very slowly during

00:06:31.942 --> 00:06:34.598
this period,
but population is also rising

00:06:34.598 --> 00:06:38.740
very slowly during this period,
so pretty much the gains in

00:06:38.740 --> 00:06:43.204
agricultural productivity were
balanced by the gains in

00:06:43.204 --> 00:06:47.502
population and the average
standard of living did not

00:06:47.502 --> 00:06:52.050
improve and we'll talk a good
bit more about that.

00:06:52.050 --> 00:06:55.992
Now why--so the question I mean
is pretty obvious why they were

00:06:55.992 --> 00:06:59.110
not able to improve agricultural
productivity,

00:06:59.110 --> 00:07:02.057
why they were not able to
significantly improve any other

00:07:02.057 --> 00:07:04.060
kind of manufacturing
productivity,

00:07:04.060 --> 00:07:07.761
why they were not able to do
anything to fight these

00:07:07.761 --> 00:07:08.560
diseases.
 

00:07:08.560 --> 00:07:11.218
It comes down to,
that not only was there no

00:07:11.218 --> 00:07:14.620
scientific knowledge as we
currently understand the word

00:07:14.620 --> 00:07:18.033
scientific,
there really wasn't any

00:07:18.033 --> 00:07:23.577
particular interest in--
intellectually in the real

00:07:23.577 --> 00:07:24.360
world.
 

00:07:24.360 --> 00:07:29.829
Everything was focused on
religion and the other world,

00:07:29.829 --> 00:07:33.670
so there was not a lot of
intellectual energy expended in

00:07:33.670 --> 00:07:37.783
trying to understand what was
going on around your feet so to

00:07:37.783 --> 00:07:38.470
speak.
 

00:07:38.470 --> 00:07:42.507
Because they had all kinds of
problems that we take for

00:07:42.507 --> 00:07:44.932
granted,
all kinds of ways of dealing

00:07:44.932 --> 00:07:47.279
with the real world just were
not even--

00:07:47.279 --> 00:07:50.440
were not really thought about
in any serious way.

00:07:50.440 --> 00:07:53.942
Sanitation, up until the
eighteenth century,

00:07:53.942 --> 00:07:58.504
up until the 1800s actually,
the sanitation in Europe was

00:07:58.504 --> 00:08:00.949
just absolutely atrocious.
 

00:08:00.949 --> 00:08:05.259
There was no system for
disposing of human waste.

00:08:05.259 --> 00:08:07.994
Nobody bothered to pay
attention to what to do with

00:08:07.994 --> 00:08:08.759
human waste.
 

00:08:08.759 --> 00:08:10.410
Feces were basically everywhere.
 

00:08:10.410 --> 00:08:14.660
Wherever you went there was
someone else's feces.

00:08:14.660 --> 00:08:18.829
In the eighteenth century the
city streets everywhere had

00:08:18.829 --> 00:08:23.074
ditches down the middle of the
street and that's where the

00:08:23.074 --> 00:08:24.639
feces got dumped.
 

00:08:24.639 --> 00:08:27.399
There were buckets inside the
house and some servant,

00:08:27.399 --> 00:08:30.583
or the housewife would take the
bucket and dump it into these

00:08:30.583 --> 00:08:31.220
ditches.
 

00:08:31.220 --> 00:08:34.573
They were also used as
latrines, people would just go

00:08:34.573 --> 00:08:38.379
out there and if they didn't
have a bucket in the house,

00:08:38.379 --> 00:08:40.850
or if they didn't have a house,
go in and do it in the latrine.

00:08:40.850 --> 00:08:46.580
Again, in each case--I was in
Belize City in Latin--

00:08:46.580 --> 00:08:50.328
in Central America as you know,
not that many years ago in the

00:08:50.328 --> 00:08:53.279
middle of the street there's one
big latrine,

00:08:53.279 --> 00:08:55.639
and the stink was just
incredible.

00:08:55.639 --> 00:08:59.754
Now you didn't actually have
to--were not required to

00:08:59.754 --> 00:09:04.029
actually take your bucket of
feces and dump them in the

00:09:04.029 --> 00:09:06.437
street,
you could throw them out your

00:09:06.437 --> 00:09:06.840
window.
 

00:09:06.840 --> 00:09:10.821
But eventually people did start
thinking about that,

00:09:10.821 --> 00:09:14.960
and the issue was not to dump
it on someone's head.

00:09:14.960 --> 00:09:20.289
In Edinburgh,
Scotland they rang bells at

00:09:20.289 --> 00:09:21.889
10:00 p.m.
 

00:09:21.889 --> 00:09:25.181
at night when they figured
people should be off the street

00:09:25.181 --> 00:09:28.703
and that was the specified time
for dumping excrement out your

00:09:28.703 --> 00:09:29.340
window.
 

00:09:29.340 --> 00:09:31.428
Some of the older of you that
were properly brought up--

00:09:31.428 --> 00:09:35.428
the young men were maybe told
that you should walk on the

00:09:35.428 --> 00:09:38.929
street side when you're
escorting a young lady.

00:09:38.929 --> 00:09:40.840
Do you know what that's for?
 

00:09:40.840 --> 00:09:44.706
When stuff gets dumped out the
window it's to prevent splash

00:09:44.706 --> 00:09:47.573
from cars,
it's way earlier then cars,

00:09:47.573 --> 00:09:50.587
it was to--
so that when someone dumped

00:09:50.587 --> 00:09:56.460
stuff out the window it would--
the lady would be under some

00:09:56.460 --> 00:09:59.220
kind of awnings there.
 

00:09:59.220 --> 00:10:02.389
It wasn't only the common
people, the poor,

00:10:02.389 --> 00:10:06.009
the uneducated that were living
in such filth,

00:10:06.009 --> 00:10:10.000
it went right up to the royalty
and we have records of this.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:13.038
In 1665, there was a great
plague in London,

00:10:13.038 --> 00:10:16.644
one of those that I've showed
you there and that's the one

00:10:16.644 --> 00:10:20.211
that--
written about by Robinson

00:10:20.211 --> 00:10:23.820
Crusoe author,
Daniel Dafoe.

00:10:23.820 --> 00:10:27.244
The King, Charles II,
and his court took his refuge

00:10:27.244 --> 00:10:28.820
in Oxford University.
 

00:10:28.820 --> 00:10:32.506
Now Yale is modeled after--a
lot of Yale is modeled after

00:10:32.506 --> 00:10:36.259
Oxford, so you have a good image
of what it looks like.

00:10:36.259 --> 00:10:39.029
The plague was over,
it took about a year,

00:10:39.029 --> 00:10:41.572
the plague was over,
they went back to London and

00:10:41.572 --> 00:10:43.798
just left whatever they left in
Oxford,

00:10:43.798 --> 00:10:46.970
and the cleaning people came in
and what did they find?

00:10:46.970 --> 00:10:50.072
Excrement everywhere,
they described it excrement in

00:10:50.072 --> 00:10:51.592
every corner,
in chimneys,

00:10:51.592 --> 00:10:55.000
in studies, in coal houses,
in cellars, just all over the

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:55.730
place.
 

00:10:55.730 --> 00:11:00.298
Now some of this information
comes from the diary of Samuel

00:11:00.298 --> 00:11:00.928
Pepys.
 

00:11:00.928 --> 00:11:03.129
How many of you are aware of
this?

00:11:03.129 --> 00:11:06.837
Some of you again if you've
taken history or literature,

00:11:06.837 --> 00:11:09.399
he was the famous diarist from
that.

00:11:09.399 --> 00:11:12.038
He was England's first
Secretary of the Admiralty,

00:11:12.038 --> 00:11:14.833
a Member of Parliament,
President of The Royal

00:11:14.833 --> 00:11:18.034
Scientific Society,
so he was not your ordinary

00:11:18.034 --> 00:11:18.918
average guy.
 

00:11:18.918 --> 00:11:22.589
He was educated,
had money and in the upper

00:11:22.589 --> 00:11:24.815
classes,
but he writes that -- when he

00:11:24.815 --> 00:11:26.778
had to defecate in the middle of
the night--

00:11:26.778 --> 00:11:28.759
he didn't bother to go to the
privy,

00:11:28.759 --> 00:11:35.450
he just deposited his feces in
the fireplace.

00:11:35.450 --> 00:11:39.070
You can see that it was a
smelly place to live in.

00:11:39.070 --> 00:11:45.099
Now along with no concern or no
thought about where you deposit

00:11:45.099 --> 00:11:48.956
your excrement,
the idea of keeping drinking

00:11:48.956 --> 00:11:53.018
water separate from this
excrement was not in anybody's

00:11:53.018 --> 00:11:53.620
mind.
 

00:11:53.620 --> 00:11:58.139
That very often if there were
public holes or someplace where

00:11:58.139 --> 00:12:01.230
the public could go to do their
thing,

00:12:01.230 --> 00:12:04.110
then maybe right next to it was
a drinking fountain.

00:12:04.110 --> 00:12:10.572
In terms of the waste in the
streets, it wasn't just feces

00:12:10.572 --> 00:12:16.808
but everything else was just
dumped into the streets.

00:12:16.808 --> 00:12:21.695
England especially had lots of
animals, Europe had animals,

00:12:21.695 --> 00:12:25.063
unlike China,
and when animals died--just

00:12:25.063 --> 00:12:28.769
left in the middle of the street
to rot.

00:12:28.769 --> 00:12:30.808
Butchers that pulled out the
entrails,

00:12:30.808 --> 00:12:32.720
the guts of the animals and
inedible parts,

00:12:32.720 --> 00:12:36.807
dump it in the street and so
the streets are just full of not

00:12:36.807 --> 00:12:40.690
only human excrement but the
waste of all the animals,

00:12:40.690 --> 00:12:44.370
and of course the flies and
insects lay their eggs in it and

00:12:44.370 --> 00:12:49.100
grow,
and it's very unsanitary.

00:12:49.100 --> 00:12:54.259
Dead people were not handled
any better than this.

00:12:54.259 --> 00:12:57.692
As more people died,
the urban cemeteries got filled

00:12:57.692 --> 00:12:58.029
up.
 

00:12:58.029 --> 00:13:02.995
There was not so much space and
so they stopped burying the poor

00:13:02.995 --> 00:13:06.245
people in--
properly in cemeteries but just

00:13:06.245 --> 00:13:10.408
what they call 'poor holes,'
just large pits in which piles

00:13:10.408 --> 00:13:13.710
of bodies were just laid out
side by side,

00:13:13.710 --> 00:13:17.500
row by row, and row on top of
row and they were not closed

00:13:17.500 --> 00:13:19.028
until they were full.
 

00:13:19.028 --> 00:13:23.232
You had these pits of rotting
bodies just festering there in

00:13:23.232 --> 00:13:27.649
the middle of all the cities
that had enough people to bury.

00:13:27.649 --> 00:13:32.205
Of course the stench was just
overwhelming and the rich people

00:13:32.205 --> 00:13:35.940
were not buried in these pits
but if they were--

00:13:35.940 --> 00:13:37.649
they could be buried in
cemeteries,

00:13:37.649 --> 00:13:40.515
but if they were really
important they bought space in

00:13:40.515 --> 00:13:43.490
the church crypt or they
contributed money and got space

00:13:43.490 --> 00:13:44.788
in the church crypt.
 

00:13:44.788 --> 00:13:49.261
Many of you have undoubtedly
gone to churches and in the

00:13:49.261 --> 00:13:53.898
basement they've got these
crypts of dead people and guess

00:13:53.898 --> 00:13:54.629
what?
 

00:13:54.629 --> 00:13:59.850
They were rotting and stank,
so the churches stank.

00:13:59.850 --> 00:14:03.408
One quote is that 'they stank
out parson and

00:14:03.408 --> 00:14:08.460
congregation'--that people just
couldn't stand to be there.

00:14:08.460 --> 00:14:13.183
In 1742, Dr. Johnson,
who you know wrote The Life of

00:14:13.183 --> 00:14:16.796
Boswell--excuse me,
Boswell's Life of

00:14:16.796 --> 00:14:20.778
Johnson, so he's quoting
Johnson.

00:14:20.778 --> 00:14:28.176
Described London as a city,
"Which abounds with such

00:14:28.176 --> 00:14:36.629
heaps of filth as a savage would
look on with amazement."

00:14:36.629 --> 00:14:40.722
The death rate--cities were so
unhealthy from all this filth

00:14:40.722 --> 00:14:44.538
that the death rates were
enormously high and cities did

00:14:44.538 --> 00:14:46.620
not keep themselves going.
 

00:14:46.620 --> 00:14:49.552
If left to itself a city's
population would just disappear

00:14:49.552 --> 00:14:52.330
and some estimates are that
about every generation,

00:14:52.330 --> 00:14:56.830
about a third of the
inhabitants of a city would die.

00:14:56.830 --> 00:14:59.710
I mean everybody died,
but the population left--

00:14:59.710 --> 00:15:03.721
the city just left to itself
would go down by a third in

00:15:03.721 --> 00:15:06.633
every generation,
and the only reason that cities

00:15:06.633 --> 00:15:09.447
were able to prosper was that in
the countryside where things

00:15:09.447 --> 00:15:11.370
were healthier just because of
space,

00:15:11.370 --> 00:15:15.368
there wasn't the demography,
there wasn't the crowding of

00:15:15.368 --> 00:15:18.509
people that constantly the
excess births,

00:15:18.509 --> 00:15:21.942
the excess population from the
countryside would keep migrating

00:15:21.942 --> 00:15:25.097
into the cities because they had
primogeniture in England,

00:15:25.097 --> 00:15:26.038
for instance.
 

00:15:26.038 --> 00:15:28.807
Only the oldest son could
inherit the land,

00:15:28.807 --> 00:15:32.892
so younger sons had to migrate
into the cities or into the army

00:15:32.892 --> 00:15:35.658
and that's what kept the cities
going.

00:15:35.658 --> 00:15:42.011
There's a constant stream of
people coming in from the

00:15:42.011 --> 00:15:43.690
countryside.
 

00:15:43.690 --> 00:15:45.548
Now it's not only London and
the great cities,

00:15:45.548 --> 00:15:47.658
and it's not only that part of
Europe,

00:15:47.658 --> 00:15:51.090
but we have descriptions of
some of the other cities,

00:15:51.090 --> 00:15:54.460
and one of them is currently
politically very relevant.

00:15:54.460 --> 00:15:58.934
It is Jerusalem and now all the
great Western religions claim

00:15:58.934 --> 00:16:03.335
that Jerusalem is central to
their religion and they compete

00:16:03.335 --> 00:16:06.260
viciously;
they fight viciously over

00:16:06.260 --> 00:16:07.090
Jerusalem.
 

00:16:07.090 --> 00:16:11.370
They all claim that they've
been interested forever in this,

00:16:11.370 --> 00:16:14.371
but in fact,
… until Napoleon's

00:16:14.371 --> 00:16:17.778
expedition to Egypt in the
Middle East,

00:16:17.778 --> 00:16:21.596
it was totally ignored as a
physical thing from the crusades

00:16:21.596 --> 00:16:23.990
to Napoleon it was totally
ignored.

00:16:23.990 --> 00:16:28.039
In 1840 it was a tiny town of
15,000 people;

00:16:28.039 --> 00:16:30.629
7,000 Jews;
5,000 Muslims;

00:16:30.629 --> 00:16:33.320
3,000 Christians from the
records that we have.

00:16:33.320 --> 00:16:37.410
In a place like that,
presumably the seed of the

00:16:37.410 --> 00:16:41.827
Western religions,
the feces were 50 feet deep and

00:16:41.827 --> 00:16:46.919
had been collecting since the
destruction of the second temple

00:16:46.919 --> 00:16:48.340
by the Romans.
 

00:16:48.340 --> 00:16:53.549
Before the Romans destroyed
Jerusalem there was some sort of

00:16:53.549 --> 00:16:57.878
sanitation going on,
but between then and 1840 the

00:16:57.878 --> 00:17:00.440
feces just kept going up.
 

00:17:00.440 --> 00:17:02.970
Of course in this filth
everybody was sick.

00:17:02.970 --> 00:17:06.430
Basically everyone had malaria,
and malaria was endemic there.

00:17:06.430 --> 00:17:09.000
When cholera came through,
which it came periodically,

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:13.998
75% of the people would die of
it and one quote describing

00:17:13.998 --> 00:17:17.288
this,
"The sanitary condition of

00:17:17.288 --> 00:17:22.465
the city of God insure that any
pilgrim who sought to spend his

00:17:22.465 --> 00:17:27.559
last days on earth there could
look forward to fulfilling that

00:17:27.559 --> 00:17:30.650
ideal with great dispatch."
 

00:17:30.650 --> 00:17:33.220
Personal cleanliness:
this was also unknown.

00:17:33.220 --> 00:17:36.866
We have one professor of
medieval history who gives a

00:17:36.866 --> 00:17:40.795
great lecture and if he ever
gives it as a public lecture

00:17:40.795 --> 00:17:42.759
that I've seen him give.
 

00:17:42.759 --> 00:17:44.868
If he ever gives it again
absolutely go.

00:17:44.868 --> 00:17:49.105
It's called '1,000 Years
Without a Bath,' so this is in

00:17:49.105 --> 00:17:52.265
Europe,
the Romans were very careful

00:17:52.265 --> 00:17:57.016
about personal cleanliness and
they built these great big

00:17:57.016 --> 00:17:57.779
baths.
 

00:17:57.779 --> 00:18:02.779
… Have you visited the
baths of Caracalla in Rome;

00:18:02.779 --> 00:18:03.598
a couple of you have.
 

00:18:03.598 --> 00:18:07.362
How about Bath--the city in
England named after its baths

00:18:07.362 --> 00:18:08.368
and so forth?
 

00:18:08.368 --> 00:18:12.709
All these are Roman creations,
so the Romans very careful,

00:18:12.709 --> 00:18:16.895
as much as they could in a
place like that with personal

00:18:16.895 --> 00:18:17.808
hygiene.
 

00:18:17.808 --> 00:18:20.630
But after the fall of Rome the
morality changes,

00:18:20.630 --> 00:18:23.407
the church takes over,
and the church wants people to

00:18:23.407 --> 00:18:26.078
concentrate on their souls not
on their bodies,

00:18:26.078 --> 00:18:30.309
and washing was considered too
much of a sign of preoccupation

00:18:30.309 --> 00:18:33.838
with the body,
and especially for women.

00:18:33.838 --> 00:18:41.913
It's not good for women to pay
too much attention to their

00:18:41.913 --> 00:18:43.190
bodies.
 

00:18:43.190 --> 00:18:45.916
Europeans at that time,
boasted and you've probably

00:18:45.916 --> 00:18:49.190
heard this that they only wash
three times in their lives.

00:18:49.190 --> 00:18:50.808
How many of you have ever heard
that?

00:18:50.808 --> 00:18:52.858
Once when they're born,
once when they get married,

00:18:52.858 --> 00:18:55.640
and once when they die they get
washed,

00:18:55.640 --> 00:18:58.867
and the rest of that--not only
didn't they wash they thought

00:18:58.867 --> 00:19:01.660
that water that you washed with
carried disease,

00:19:01.660 --> 00:19:06.115
contagion, various theories and
that if you washed you would

00:19:06.115 --> 00:19:08.910
probably get sick from the
washing.

00:19:08.910 --> 00:19:11.694
The solution was not
cleanliness--the solution to the

00:19:11.694 --> 00:19:13.460
bad conditions--
but perfume,

00:19:13.460 --> 00:19:17.460
and perfume comes up in this
era because people stank so much

00:19:17.460 --> 00:19:20.221
that,
if they had the money,

00:19:20.221 --> 00:19:22.579
they would buy perfume.
 

00:19:22.579 --> 00:19:25.618
Anybody know why--yes?
 

00:19:25.618 --> 00:19:30.684
Student:  Was the water
likely to make you sick because

00:19:30.684 --> 00:19:32.180
it was so dirty?
 

00:19:32.180 --> 00:19:35.520
Prof: Good question,
was the water likely to make

00:19:35.520 --> 00:19:36.250
them sick?
 

00:19:36.250 --> 00:19:38.630
If they drank the water, yes.
 

00:19:38.630 --> 00:19:40.650
If they washed in the water, no.
 

00:19:40.650 --> 00:19:43.529
There's very little in
temperate zone water that's

00:19:43.529 --> 00:19:45.470
going to get through your skin.
 

00:19:45.470 --> 00:19:48.740
In tropical zones there can be
parasites in there and they can

00:19:48.740 --> 00:19:52.587
be dangerous,
but in Europe I'm not sort of

00:19:52.587 --> 00:19:59.078
aware of anything that washing
in the water will get you sick.

00:19:59.078 --> 00:20:02.392
Student:  On the hand if
you wash yourself and it stays

00:20:02.392 --> 00:20:05.651
on your skin and then you eat or
something could you then get

00:20:05.651 --> 00:20:06.140
sick?
 

00:20:06.140 --> 00:20:08.596
Prof: Yes,
if you wash yourself,

00:20:08.596 --> 00:20:12.218
it stays on your skin and then
you eat with your unwashed

00:20:12.218 --> 00:20:14.417
hands--
well probably what was on there

00:20:14.417 --> 00:20:16.338
before you washed is going to be
worse.

00:20:16.338 --> 00:20:20.057
In general, I think nobody
washed unless something comes

00:20:20.057 --> 00:20:23.710
off--the burden of whatever's on
the skin gets less.

00:20:23.710 --> 00:20:27.278
All of these things are what we
modern people think about,

00:20:27.278 --> 00:20:30.305
but obviously,
back then, just these kind of

00:20:30.305 --> 00:20:33.963
very simple straightforward
questions were not really

00:20:33.963 --> 00:20:35.019
considered.
 

00:20:35.019 --> 00:20:37.078
People back then,
George Washington,

00:20:37.078 --> 00:20:39.548
King George wore wigs--anybody
know why?

00:20:39.548 --> 00:20:44.435
Some of you probably know why
they wear wigs--underneath the

00:20:44.435 --> 00:20:49.068
wig was--
Student:  Head lice.

00:20:49.068 --> 00:20:51.167
Prof: Lots of lice,
shaved heads,

00:20:51.167 --> 00:20:52.029
they had lice.
 

00:20:52.029 --> 00:20:54.327
Lice was endemic,
they couldn't get rid of it,

00:20:54.327 --> 00:20:55.808
so they shaved their heads.
 

00:20:55.808 --> 00:20:58.651
I think we just saw that on
television with the John Adams

00:20:58.651 --> 00:20:59.048
story.
 

00:20:59.048 --> 00:21:02.740
Every so often--did any of you
see that TV show?

00:21:02.740 --> 00:21:09.801
HBO--anyway he takes off his
wig and there he is bald,

00:21:09.801 --> 00:21:13.400
that was to prevent lice.
 

00:21:13.400 --> 00:21:19.336
One of the reasons--one of the
major reasons for this lack of

00:21:19.336 --> 00:21:24.578
population growth for hundreds
of years in Europe,

00:21:24.578 --> 00:21:27.569
just no idea about sanitation,
hygiene,

00:21:27.569 --> 00:21:30.308
any of this kind of stuff.
 

00:21:30.308 --> 00:21:36.048
Another aspect which you'll be
reading about is infanticide.

00:21:36.048 --> 00:21:39.800
Infanticide was a very large
factor in European demography

00:21:39.800 --> 00:21:43.027
and the rest of the world,
as you will read about,

00:21:43.027 --> 00:21:45.660
but in Europe it was very
important.

00:21:45.660 --> 00:21:52.440
There was always a level of
infanticide and--

00:21:52.440 --> 00:21:55.789
of various sorts but in the
eighteenth and nineteenth

00:21:55.789 --> 00:21:58.108
centuries it apparently
exploded--

00:21:58.108 --> 00:22:01.259
the number of kids that were
done away with.

00:22:01.259 --> 00:22:07.267
In Milan, from 1840s to 1860s,
one third of all children born

00:22:07.267 --> 00:22:10.595
to married parents--
we're not talking about

00:22:10.595 --> 00:22:14.025
unmarried situations--
were left at foundling homes

00:22:14.025 --> 00:22:18.390
and in foundling homes the death
rate was near 100%.

00:22:18.390 --> 00:22:21.585
More than half of all the
children born to working class

00:22:21.585 --> 00:22:23.910
parents were left in foundling
homes,

00:22:23.910 --> 00:22:27.976
and almost all the illegitimate
children were abandoned and the

00:22:27.976 --> 00:22:30.575
death rates--
it was a form of infanticide,

00:22:30.575 --> 00:22:32.858
you just gave them to a
foundling home,

00:22:32.858 --> 00:22:35.321
they were taken,
basically, no care of,

00:22:35.321 --> 00:22:36.099
they died.
 

00:22:36.099 --> 00:22:38.848
It was out of sight.
 

00:22:38.848 --> 00:22:42.291
Again, not just the ordinary
ignorant person but you all know

00:22:42.291 --> 00:22:43.670
Jean-Jacques Rousseau?
 

00:22:43.670 --> 00:22:47.173
The famous French
philosophe who wrote a

00:22:47.173 --> 00:22:50.680
lot that encouraged the American
Revolution.

00:22:50.680 --> 00:22:54.785
This is a quote from him,
"My third child was thus

00:22:54.785 --> 00:22:59.118
deposited in a foundling home
just like the first two,

00:22:59.118 --> 00:23:01.690
and I did the same with the two
following.

00:23:01.690 --> 00:23:04.028
I had five in all.
 

00:23:04.028 --> 00:23:05.890
The arrangement seemed to me so
good,

00:23:05.890 --> 00:23:08.422
so sensible,
so appropriate that,

00:23:08.422 --> 00:23:11.348
if I did not boast of it
publicly,

00:23:11.348 --> 00:23:14.650
it was solely out of regard for
their mother."

00:23:14.650 --> 00:23:19.734
There was no--here they're
abandoning these children to

00:23:19.734 --> 00:23:24.538
almost certain death and
it--there was just no moral

00:23:24.538 --> 00:23:27.930
compunction about it whatsoever.
 

00:23:27.930 --> 00:23:31.368
Aside from absolute abandonment
to foundling homes or …

00:23:31.368 --> 00:23:33.400
just leaving them in the
streets--

00:23:33.400 --> 00:23:36.588
you'll read about American and
England where the kids were just

00:23:36.588 --> 00:23:38.029
often left in the streets.
 

00:23:38.029 --> 00:23:43.486
Another mechanism was sending
out children to nurse with wet

00:23:43.486 --> 00:23:49.126
nurses and the death rate of wet
nurse children was enormously

00:23:49.126 --> 00:23:49.960
high.
 

00:23:49.960 --> 00:23:53.627
So, if parents tried to rear
their children,

00:23:53.627 --> 00:23:57.980
the death rate was about one in
six at this time.

00:23:57.980 --> 00:24:04.800
In eighteenth century France
between a half and two-thirds of

00:24:04.800 --> 00:24:09.690
infants that were sent out to
nurse died.

00:24:09.690 --> 00:24:13.078
Even at a higher death rate
were the so called baby farms,

00:24:13.078 --> 00:24:17.230
in the nineteenth century
Europe there were--

00:24:17.230 --> 00:24:19.068
it's like we call them puppy
mills now,

00:24:19.068 --> 00:24:22.636
they were baby farms,
and they took in vast numbers

00:24:22.636 --> 00:24:25.420
of children presumably to wet
nurse,

00:24:25.420 --> 00:24:28.730
but almost none of them
survived.

00:24:28.730 --> 00:24:33.336
As I showed you from these and
all kinds of reasons,

00:24:33.336 --> 00:24:37.308
about a third of children died
in infancy.

00:24:37.308 --> 00:24:42.179
The idea of being a parent and
the family idea of childrearing

00:24:42.179 --> 00:24:46.170
was completely different then we
now understand.

00:24:46.170 --> 00:24:49.112
The standard thing was a child
was born, it was almost

00:24:49.112 --> 00:24:52.386
immediately sent out to wet
nurse, someone that doesn't care

00:24:52.386 --> 00:24:53.220
about them.
 

00:24:53.220 --> 00:24:55.711
A lot was written about wet
nurses getting drunk,

00:24:55.711 --> 00:24:57.631
having the baby in bed,
getting drunk,

00:24:57.631 --> 00:25:00.328
rolling over on the baby and
squashing the baby.

00:25:00.328 --> 00:25:04.946
Whether that was an excuse or
the real reason for the child's

00:25:04.946 --> 00:25:06.410
death is unknown.
 

00:25:06.410 --> 00:25:10.642
They would wet nurse for a
couple of years and then those

00:25:10.642 --> 00:25:14.118
that were still alive would come
back home,

00:25:14.118 --> 00:25:19.140
maybe age two or three or
something,

00:25:19.140 --> 00:25:23.760
and then by age seven they
would be sent back out to work

00:25:23.760 --> 00:25:26.650
again as an apprentice
somewhere.

00:25:26.650 --> 00:25:29.535
How many have read Charles
Dickens: David

00:25:29.535 --> 00:25:32.420
Copperfield,
and Oliver Twist?

00:25:32.420 --> 00:25:34.640
What age were they sent out to
work?

00:25:34.640 --> 00:25:35.071
Seven.
 

00:25:35.071 --> 00:25:39.104
Seven is the standard age,
there are scenes of one of the

00:25:39.104 --> 00:25:43.065
Dicken's characters going to
work in a dye factory dying

00:25:43.065 --> 00:25:46.506
cloth,
and he comes out black every

00:25:46.506 --> 00:25:48.990
day, covered with the dye.
 

00:25:48.990 --> 00:25:52.480
That was quite a standard thing.
 

00:25:52.480 --> 00:25:57.406
In 1646, the rich and very
progressive town of Leyden in

00:25:57.406 --> 00:26:00.852
the Netherlands,
Lehyden was one of the most

00:26:00.852 --> 00:26:05.133
advanced places in Europe,
limited the working day for

00:26:05.133 --> 00:26:08.169
children to 14 hours,
whether the law was obeyed or

00:26:08.169 --> 00:26:11.720
not we don't know,
but children could not do that.

00:26:11.720 --> 00:26:14.320
Of course Charles Dickens is a
couple of hundred years later in

00:26:14.320 --> 00:26:15.368
the nineteenth century.
 

00:26:15.368 --> 00:26:19.909
Apparently, in every one of his
novels, there's some scene of

00:26:19.909 --> 00:26:21.650
child labor going on.
 

00:26:21.650 --> 00:26:26.035
Now I'm talking about up to the
1800s but this does not

00:26:26.035 --> 00:26:27.009
disappear.
 

00:26:27.009 --> 00:26:29.999
Now you look what Europe--the
situation Europe was in,

00:26:29.999 --> 00:26:33.440
in 1800--some of the developing
countries are currently in.

00:26:33.440 --> 00:26:37.256
So official figures from India,
the government figures,

00:26:37.256 --> 00:26:40.788
say there are 12 million child
workers in India.

00:26:40.788 --> 00:26:45.247
Opponents, activists on the
labor issue, estimate that it's

00:26:45.247 --> 00:26:49.318
closer to 60 million children in
India are working.

00:26:49.318 --> 00:26:54.923
They do have child labor laws
now in India and they prohibit

00:26:54.923 --> 00:27:00.150
children under age 14 from
working in hazardous jobs.

00:27:00.150 --> 00:27:04.146
When the scandal about Gap,
our clothing manufacture Gap

00:27:04.146 --> 00:27:07.365
came out,
the factories that were

00:27:07.365 --> 00:27:13.284
investigated had children as
young as ten years old working

00:27:13.284 --> 00:27:18.282
up to 16 hours a day making the
dungarees …

00:27:18.282 --> 00:27:20.118
that we wear.
 

00:27:20.118 --> 00:27:25.228
All of this sort of misery
leads not only to physical

00:27:25.228 --> 00:27:29.650
misery but change in attitude
toward life,

00:27:29.650 --> 00:27:34.410
and death came very easily,
it was very common and so life

00:27:34.410 --> 00:27:35.578
was cheaper.
 

00:27:35.578 --> 00:27:39.625
There's no question about it
from the literature that life

00:27:39.625 --> 00:27:42.108
was cheaper then we consider
now.

00:27:42.108 --> 00:27:45.288
Because children especially
were so likely to die,

00:27:45.288 --> 00:27:48.640
as well as anyone else,
it was considered imprudent,

00:27:48.640 --> 00:27:52.030
not wise, to be particularly
affectionate with or emotionally

00:27:52.030 --> 00:27:54.180
entwined with any other human
being.

00:27:54.180 --> 00:27:57.627
Your husband might die
immediately, your kids might

00:27:57.627 --> 00:27:59.490
die, your wife might die.
 

00:27:59.490 --> 00:28:02.730
And so as far as we can tell
from the writings of the period,

00:28:02.730 --> 00:28:04.958
what we call affective
relationships,

00:28:04.958 --> 00:28:08.608
emotional relationships were
rather cool in this period,

00:28:08.608 --> 00:28:14.480
except of course violent anger
which always pops out.

00:28:14.480 --> 00:28:20.426
Going back to this,
here's all these problems,

00:28:20.426 --> 00:28:27.299
and what did people do about
some of these things?

00:28:38.279 --> 00:28:42.794
An idea of disease comes from
the Greeks and probably farther

00:28:42.794 --> 00:28:47.327
back then the Greeks,
that the body is controlled by

00:28:47.327 --> 00:28:50.829
four humors,
fluids that run around the

00:28:50.829 --> 00:28:55.118
body, something like the Chi of
Oriental thought.

00:28:55.118 --> 00:28:58.460
And these four humorous must be
in balance.

00:28:58.460 --> 00:29:02.171
When you got sick the problem
was that the humors got out of

00:29:02.171 --> 00:29:02.798
balance.
 

00:29:02.798 --> 00:29:07.029
One of the things you did was
get bled.

00:29:07.029 --> 00:29:12.565
That was a standard procedure;
let the blood flow because that

00:29:12.565 --> 00:29:16.068
gets rid of the evil humors.
 

00:29:16.068 --> 00:29:18.917
George Washington was
apparently killed by an excess

00:29:18.917 --> 00:29:22.381
of bloodletting,
so when he was older he got

00:29:22.381 --> 00:29:26.650
quite sick and the doctors--
while he was sick,

00:29:26.650 --> 00:29:31.720
bled five pints of blood out of
him and then he died.

00:29:31.720 --> 00:29:34.701
We take--when we go to take
blood they take one pint and

00:29:34.701 --> 00:29:37.900
they consider that sort of the
maximum safe amount for young

00:29:37.900 --> 00:29:38.930
healthy people.
 

00:29:38.930 --> 00:29:42.328
Here he was old and sick,
five pints, he dies.

